instruction: I'm characterizing a 256×256 SRAM macro for high-performance computing applications requiring robust read/write functionality. The hierarchical architecture comprises 16 RAM_64X64 subarrays, organized into a 4×4 configuration with 64-bit data buses, totaling 65,536 bits. Key operational parameters include a 3.3V supply voltage, address setup time of 50ns relative to clock edges, and precisely timed control signals: read enable (RO) activates at 150ns, write enable (WENB) at 100ns, with a 25ns clock period (40MHz). The simulation employs transient analysis with 1ns resolution over 100ns duration to validate critical timing margins—particularly address decoder propagation (YDEC_64TMP blocks) and I/O buffer latency (XIO_64 instances). Configure the analysis to monitor worst-case access time by probing all 256 output bits (AO<255:0>) during simultaneous read/write operations across multiple subarrays, ensuring proper setup/hold margins are maintained under maximum capacitive loading from the column multiplexers.

I'm characterizing a 512×256-bit SRAM module operating at 3.3V supply voltage for timing and functionality verification. The memory architecture employs hierarchical organization with 8×8 memory cell arrays arranged in 64×64 sub-blocks, utilizing a 3-bit address decoder with enable control. Key timing parameters from the stimulus include: address setup time of 50ns with 100ps rise/fall times, write enable (WENB) activation at 100ns, read enable (RO) assertion at 150ns, and clock (CL) rising edge at 25ns. The simulation requires transient analysis spanning 400ns to capture complete write/read cycles across multiple address patterns, with specific attention to critical timing paths including address decoder propagation (200ns period for ADD<0>), write pulse width (25ns active low for WENB), and read access time from clock edge. Please configure the simulation to monitor all address, data, and control signals with particular focus on setup/hold timing margins and signal integrity across the distributed RC network of the hierarchical bitlines and wordlines.

I'm characterizing the timing performance of an 8x8-bit SRAM module operating at 40MHz for embedded memory applications. The design uses a 3.3V supply voltage and features a synchronous interface with clock (CL), read output (RO), and write enable (WENB) control signals. The memory core employs a hierarchical 64-bit array built from cascaded RAM_1X1 cells using 0.4μm CMOS technology with NMOS access transistors (W=4μm) and inverter-based storage cells (NMOS W=2μm, PMOS W=3μm). Critical timing parameters include: 25ns clock period, 100ns write enable activation delay, and 150ns read output enable delay. The write data pattern from the DGEN_8 subcircuit generates bit-serial pulses with periods ranging from 400ns (LSB) to 3200ns (MSB) to verify address decoding. I need to perform transient analysis with 1ns resolution over 1μs duration to measure setup/hold times and access delays while monitoring all data bus transitions. The simulation should use BSIM3 models with nominal process corners and save waveform data for CL, RD[7:0], RO, WD[7:0], and WENB signals to verify proper read/write functionality across all memory locations.

instruction: I'm characterizing an 8x8 SRAM memory array for embedded applications requiring verification of read/write functionality and timing performance. The design implements a standard 6T cell topology with hierarchical organization using 64 individual ram_1x1 cells arranged in an 8x8 matrix. Key specifications include: 3.3V supply voltage, 0.4μm NMOS/PMOS channel lengths with 4μm/3μm widths respectively for access transistors, and 5fF bitline capacitance. The simulation setup uses pulsed address inputs with 50ns period and 0.1ns rise/fall times, while control signals (CL, WENB, RO, ADDENB) have precisely coordinated timing relationships. I need to perform transient analysis from 0 to 4μs with 1ns resolution to validate write operations at 100ns intervals and subsequent read operations, monitoring critical nodes including address lines, data I/O, and control signals to verify proper cell selection, data retention, and access timing margins. The simulation should capture worst-case timing scenarios including address decoding delays and bitline settling characteristics.

instruction: I'm characterizing a 768×256-bit SRAM macro operating at 3.3V for timing and functionality verification. The memory architecture employs a hierarchical structure with 12×64×64 sub-arrays organized in a 3×4 configuration, utilizing 64-bit I/O data paths. The testbench includes comprehensive address pattern generation with specific timing: ADD<0> at 400ns period, ADD<1> at 800ns, and ADD<2> at 1600ns, with 50ns setup time and 100ps rise/fall times. Control signals are precisely timed with CL rising at 25ns, WENB and ADDENB pulsing at 100ns, and RO activating at 150ns. I need to perform transient analysis to verify critical timing parameters including address setup/hold times relative to clock edges, write enable pulse width (24.9ns minimum), and read access time from clock to valid data output. The simulation should run for 400ns to capture multiple memory cycles and verify proper write/read operations across different address locations with the data pattern generator providing comprehensive test vectors.

I'm characterizing an 8x8 SRAM memory array for timing and functionality verification in a 3.3V CMOS process. The design consists of a hierarchical 64-bit memory core built from 64 individual 1x1 RAM cells, with peripheral I/O circuitry for read/write operations. Key transistor parameters include NMOS devices at L=0.4μm/W=4μm and PMOS at L=0.4μm/W=3-8μm depending on the cell. instruction: I'm characterizing a 64x64 SRAM macro for embedded memory applications operating at 3.3V supply voltage. The design employs a hierarchical architecture with 8x8 memory blocks organized in a 64-bit word configuration, utilizing 6T SRAM cells with access transistors at 0.4μm channel length and 4μm width. The peripheral circuitry includes dynamic latches (DLT-CL) with 0.4μm NMOS and PMOS devices, and specialized I/O buffers with 4x drive strength. Key timing parameters are: 50ns address setup time, 25ns clock rise time, 200ns cycle period for write operations, and 150ns read enable activation. The simulation should capture access timing, write margin, and read stability with 1ns resolution over 100ns duration, ensuring proper cell selection through the 3-bit address decoder and verifying data integrity through the hierarchical bitline structure.

instruction: I'm characterizing an 8-line CMOS address decoder for a 3.3V SRAM memory array. The design goal is to validate the timing performance and address decoding functionality of this y-decoder circuit. The topology consists of a 3-to-8 decoder using NAND3 gates with complementary inputs, followed by dynamic latches (DLT-CL) and buffered output drivers. Key parameters include: 3.3V supply voltage, 0.4μm NMOS/PMOS channel lengths with 4μ/8μ widths for standard inverters, and 20pF capacitive loading on all output address lines (A0-A7). The simulation setup uses pulsed input signals for address bits IN0-IN2 with 200ns, 400ns, and 800ns periods respectively, plus a 200ns period enable signal and 25ns clock pulse. I need to perform transient analysis from 0 to 2μs with 1ns resolution to measure critical timing parameters including address setup time, decoder propagation delay, and output rise/fall times under maximum capacitive loading conditions. The simulation should capture all address transitions to verify proper one-hot output encoding and assess power consumption during switching events.

instruction: I am characterizing a 4-bit binary adder circuit implemented in a 130nm CMOS process (PROL013 PDK) for low-power digital applications. The design goal is to verify functional correctness and measure propagation delay under typical operating conditions. The circuit topology is a standard carry-lookahead or ripple-carry architecture with 8 input bits (a[3:0], b[3:0]) and 4 output bits (result[3:0]) plus carry-out. Key parameters include: VDD = HIGH (typically 1.2V), VSS = 0V ground, and transistor models from the prol013.mod library. I require comprehensive probing of all input and output signals to verify binary addition accuracy across multiple test vectors, plus average voltage measurements on each result bit to quantify logic levels. The analysis must include proper convergence settings with fss_sim_acc_level=1 to ensure reliable digital timing characterization.

I'm designing a 1280x1024 TFT-LCD display driver for high-resolution panel applications. The topology consists of a hierarchical row-column matrix with 1024 scan lines and differential data inputs (datap/datam). The display is partitioned into 16 sub-arrays using c3x320x256 blocks, each containing 81,920 pixels arranged in 320 columns and 256 rows. Key parameters include: 2V common electrode voltage (vcom), 4.07μs line time (ltime), 1kΩ data and scan line resistances, and data voltage swing from -10V to +12V.

The simulation requires transient analysis to characterize pixel charging behavior and row/column timing. I need to monitor pixel node voltages across the array during the 50μs simulation with 0.1μs resolution. The test pattern uses complementary PWL sources on datap/datam with 30ns delay from scan activation and 20ns transition times. Please configure the analysis to capture pixel settling characteristics, crosstalk effects, and verify proper row sequential scanning with the hierarchical timing scheme. Use TT process corner models and ensure proper convergence with reltol=3e-4 and abstol=1e-10 settings.

The topology employs a hierarchical row/column scanning architecture with 256 scan lines and differential data inputs (datap/datam) to drive RGB subpixels through c3x80x64 and c3x80x64_vscan subcircuits. Key timing parameters include: line time (ltime) of 4.07μs, data voltage swing from -10V to +12V, scan voltage swing from -25V to +30V, and common electrode voltage (vcom) at 2V. The pixel circuit uses 5μm x 5μm TFTs with 150fF storage capacitance and 0.2pF parasitic capacitance. I need to perform transient analysis to characterize the pixel charging behavior and verify the scanning sequence timing. Set up the simulation with 0.1μs time steps for 50μs duration to capture multiple line periods, monitoring pixel node voltages and scan line currents to ensure proper settling within the 20ns data setup/hold windows. Use TT process corner models with reltol=3e-4 for convergence.

instruction:
I'm designing a 1280x1024 TFT-LCD display driver array for high-resolution panel applications. The topology consists of a hierarchical pixel matrix organized into 16 sub-arrays (X1-X16) using c3x320x256 and c3x320x256_vscan subcircuits, with each pixel containing RGB TFT elements. Key parameters include: 2V common electrode voltage (Vcom), 4.07μs line time (ltime), 1kΩ data/scan line resistances, and data voltages of +12V (data_h) and -10V (data_l). The pixel circuitry uses 5μm x 5μm TFTs with 150fF storage capacitance (CLC) and 0.2pF parasitic capacitance (Cst).

I need to perform transient analysis to characterize the pixel charging behavior and timing performance. The simulation should run for 50μs with 0.1μs resolution, monitoring pixel node voltages and TFT switching characteristics. The analysis must verify proper pixel settling within the 4.07μs line time and ensure adequate voltage retention across the frame period. Use TT process corner models from the model.lib library with convergence settings: reltol=3e-4, abstol=1e-10. Probe critical nodes including pixel storage capacitors and TFT drain/source terminals to validate the scanning waveform timing and data signal integrity.

The topology consists of a hierarchical row/column scanning architecture with 256 scan lines and differential data inputs (datap/datam). I need to perform transient analysis to characterize the pixel charging behavior and verify the scanning sequence. The simulation should run for 50μs with 0.1μs resolution, using TT process corner models from model.lib. Monitor the pixel node voltages in the first sub-pixel array to verify proper charging dynamics and timing synchronization across the display matrix.

I'm characterizing a 256x256 SRAM array for high-density memory applications requiring robust read/write functionality verification. The architecture comprises 16 hierarchical 64x64 memory blocks organized in a 4x4 configuration, creating a 256-bit wide data bus with 8-bit address decoding. The design operates at 3.3V supply voltage with critical timing parameters: 25ns clock period (40MHz), 50ns address enable setup, and 100ns write enable activation. 

The simulation employs transient analysis with 1ns resolution over 100ns duration to capture worst-case access patterns. Key measurements include setup/hold timing verification for address lines ADD<2:0> relative to CLK, write cycle analysis through WD<255:0> to AO<255:0> data path, and read access timing from RD<255:0> outputs. The test sequence exercises all address combinations with alternating data patterns to validate cell stability and peripheral circuit functionality including the YDEC_64TMP address decoders and hierarchical I/O structures.

Convergence settings use default Newton-Raphson iterations with GMIN stepping enabled. All 256 output bits must settle within 15ns of clock edges while maintaining signal integrity across the resistive interconnect network (0.02Ω line resistance, 5fF load capacitance).

I'm characterizing a 512×256-bit SRAM module operating at 3.3V supply voltage for read/write timing analysis. The memory architecture employs hierarchical organization with 64×64 memory blocks, address decoders, and I/O circuitry. Key timing parameters from the stimulus include: address setup time of 50ns with 100ps rise/fall times, write enable (WENB) activation at 100ns, read output enable (RO) at 150ns, and clock (CL) rising edge at 25ns. The address pattern uses binary-weighted periods (ADD<0>: 400ns, ADD<1>: 800ns, ADD<2>: 1600ns) to exercise different memory locations. I need to perform transient analysis with 1ns resolution for 100ns duration to verify critical timing margins including address-to-clock setup (25ns), write pulse width (25ns), and read access time from clock edge. The simulation should capture all 64 write data lines (WD<63:0>) and read outputs (RD<63:0>) to validate simultaneous multi-bit operation and detect potential write contention or read disturbs.

I'm characterizing an 8x8 SRAM array for embedded memory applications requiring robust read/write functionality verification. The design employs a standard 6T-cell architecture with hierarchical organization: 64 individual 1x1 memory cells arranged in an 8x8 matrix, controlled by 3-bit address decoding (ADD<0:2>) through a ydec_8 decoder with address enable (ADDENB). The interface circuitry (xio_8) manages bidirectional data lines with separate read (RD<0:7>) and write (WD<0:7>) buses. Key parameters include 3.3V supply voltage, 0.4μm NMOS/PMOS channel lengths (L=0.4U), with cell access transistors at W=4μm and peripheral logic transistors ranging from W=4μm to W=20μm. The simulation performs transient analysis over 4μs with 1ns resolution, using pulsed control signals: clock (CL) at 25ns rising edge, write enable (WENB) at 100ns, read output (RO) at 150ns, and staggered address transitions with 50ns initial delay and periods from 400ns to 3200ns. The analysis must verify proper write/read timing margins, address decoding functionality, and data retention while monitoring critical nodes including bitlines, wordlines, and decoded address outputs under the BSIM3 nominal model library.

instruction:
I'm characterizing a 128×256-bit SRAM macro for embedded memory applications in a 3.3V CMOS process. The design employs a hierarchical architecture with 64×64 memory blocks organized in a 2×4 array, utilizing 6T cell topology with dedicated read/write circuitry. Key specifications include: 3.3V supply voltage, 50ns address setup time, and 25ns clock-to-output delay. The memory employs a 3-bit address decoder with enable signal (ADDENB) and features separate write enable (WENB) and read output (RO) control signals with 100ns and 150ns activation delays respectively.

The simulation requires transient analysis with 1ns resolution over 100ns duration to verify read/write timing margins. Critical parameters to monitor include address propagation through the decoder hierarchy, wordline activation via ydec_64tmp blocks, and data path timing through the xio_64 I/O circuits. The test sequence should exercise worst-case access patterns by toggling addresses ADD<2:0> with periods of 400ns, 800ns, and 1600ns while validating write operations through the 256-bit wide data input bus and read operations through the 64-bit output bus. Convergence settings must account for the large circuit scale with proper initialization of memory cell nodes.

I need to characterize the timing performance and signal integrity of an 8x8 static RAM array for a 3.3V CMOS memory subsystem. The design uses a hierarchical architecture with 64 individual 1-bit RAM cells organized through row/column decoders and I/O circuitry. Key parameters include: 3.3V supply voltage, 0.4μm NMOS/PMOS channel lengths with 4μ/3μ widths for access transistors, and 2μ/8μ widths for inverter drivers. The testbench includes critical timing signals: clock (CL) with 25ns rise time, write enable (WENB) pulse starting at 100ns, and read output (RO) pulse at 150ns. The data generator produces 8-bit patterns with varying periods from 400ns to 3200ns to exercise different address locations. I require transient analysis with 1ns resolution over 1μs duration to capture multiple read/write cycles. The simulation should monitor all critical nodes including clock edges, data bus transitions, and control signal timing to verify setup/hold times and access latency. Use BSIM3 model library with nominal parameters and ensure proper convergence with moderate post-processing overhead.

instruction:
I'm characterizing a 65,536-bit (256×256) SRAM macro for high-performance computing applications. The memory architecture employs a hierarchical organization with 16 instances of 64×64 RAM blocks, creating a 256×256 array with 3.3V supply voltage. The design utilizes 8-bit address decoding through YDEC_64TMP blocks and features comprehensive I/O buffering via XIO_64 interfaces.

Key timing parameters from the stimulus include: 25ns clock period (40MHz operation), 50ns address enable setup, and 100ns write enable timing. The address bus uses 3-bit decoding (ADD<2:0>) with binary-weighted pulse periods (200ns, 400ns, 800ns) for comprehensive pattern testing. The write data generator (DGEN_256) produces 256-bit patterns with varying frequencies to exercise all memory locations.

I need to perform transient analysis to verify read/write functionality and timing margins. The simulation should run for 100ns with 1ns resolution, monitoring critical signals including all 256 address outputs (AO<255:0>), 64-bit read/write data buses, and control signals (CL, WENB, RO). Please configure the analysis to capture setup/hold times and verify proper data retention across all 65,536 memory cells under the specified 3.3V operating conditions.

I need to characterize the timing performance and functional verification of an 8x8 SRAM memory array operating at 3.3V supply voltage. The design employs a standard 6T SRAM cell topology with hierarchical organization - 64 individual bit cells arranged in an 8x8 matrix, supported by address decoders, I/O circuitry, and control logic. Key transistor parameters include 0.4μm channel length for both NMOS (W=4μm) and PMOS (W=3μm) devices in the core cells, with peripheral circuits using larger drive transistors (up to W=20μm). The simulation must verify read/write operations by applying synchronized control signals: clock (CL) with 25ns rise time, write enable (WENB) and read output (RO) pulses at 100ns and 150ns respectively, and address bus (ADD<0:2>) with binary-weighted timing patterns (200ns, 400ns, 800ns periods). Configure transient analysis with 1ns resolution over 4μs duration to capture multiple access cycles, monitoring critical nodes including data lines (WD<0:7>, RD<0:7>), word lines, and internal cell storage nodes. The analysis should validate access timing margins, signal integrity, and correct data retention through complete read-write cycle sequences.

I'm characterizing a 768x256-bit SRAM macro for timing and functional verification. The design uses a hierarchical architecture with 64x64 memory blocks organized in a 12x4 array, operating at 3.3V supply voltage. The testbench includes comprehensive address pattern generation with three address bits (ADD<2:0>) having pulse periods of 1600ns, 800ns, and 400ns respectively, creating a sequential access pattern. Critical control signals include: CL (clock) with 25ns rise time, WENB (write enable) active low with 100ns delay and 200ns period, ADDENB (address enable) with 50ns delay, and RO (read output) with 150ns delay.

I need to perform transient analysis to verify read/write timing margins and access functionality. The simulation should run for 100ns with 1ns resolution to capture critical timing parameters including address setup/hold times relative to clock edges, write pulse width verification, and read access time from clock to data output. Please monitor all 64-bit data buses (WD<63:0> and RD<63:0>) to verify correct data storage and retrieval across multiple address locations, ensuring the hierarchical decoder and I/O circuitry function properly across the full memory array.

I'm characterizing an 8x8-bit static RAM module for embedded memory applications in a 3.3V CMOS process. The design goal is to verify read/write functionality, timing margins, and access characteristics. The topology consists of an 8x8 memory array built from 64 individual 1-bit RAM cells (RAM_1X1), organized with row/column decoders and I/O circuitry. Each RAM cell uses cross-coupled inverters for storage with NMOS access transistors (0.4μm channel length, 4μm width) and includes distributed RC elements (2Ω wordline resistance, 5fF bitline capacitance). The testbench employs a comprehensive stimulus pattern with clock signals (CL rising at 25ns), write enable (WENB pulsed at 100ns), read output (RO pulsed at 150ns), and data generator producing 8-bit patterns with varying periods (200ns to 3200ns). I need to perform transient analysis from 0 to 1μs with 1ns resolution to capture multiple read/write cycles, monitoring critical internal nodes including storage node voltages (RDATA/WDATA) to verify data retention and access timing. The simulation should use BSIM3 models with nominal process corners and include proper convergence settings for accurate dynamic behavior analysis.

instruction: I'm characterizing a 64x64 SRAM memory array for embedded system applications requiring high-density on-chip storage. The design goal is to validate read/write functionality and timing performance under realistic operating conditions. The topology consists of a hierarchical 6T SRAM cell array organized as 64 rows by 64 columns, with peripheral circuits including address decoders (ydec_64tmp), I/O buffers (xio_64), and data generators (dgen_64). Key parameters include a 3.3V supply voltage, 0.4μm NMOS/PMOS channel lengths with 4μm/3μm widths for the core cells, and distributed parasitic capacitances of 5fF on bitlines and 2.5fF on wordlines. The simulation uses transient analysis with 1ns resolution over 100ns duration to capture multiple read/write cycles. Address lines are driven with complementary PULSE sources having 100ps rise/fall times and periods ranging from 400ns to 1600ns, while control signals (CL, WENB, RO, ADDENB) operate with 200ns periods and specific timing relationships. The analysis must monitor all 64 data lines during simultaneous read and write operations to verify proper cell access, data integrity, and timing margins including setup/hold requirements.

instruction: I'm characterizing the timing performance of an 8-line CMOS row decoder (Y-decoder) for a 3.3V SRAM array. The circuit implements a 3-to-8 decoder topology using NAND3 pre-decoding logic followed by dynamic latches (DLT-CL) with clocked evaluation. Key transistor parameters include: 0.4μm channel length for core logic (20μm PMOS/10μm NMOS width in NAND3, 8μm/4μm in inverters), with specialized output buffers (YDEC_BUF64) using cascaded inverter chains for heavy 20pF capacitive loading on each address line. The simulation setup applies 3.3V supply with address inputs (IN0, IN1, IN2) pulsed at 200ns, 400ns, and 800ns periods respectively, enable signal (ENB) at 200ns period, and clock (CL) rising at 25ns. I need transient analysis to measure address access time and decoder propagation delay under worst-case capacitive loading conditions. Configure the simulation with 1ns resolution over 2μs duration to capture multiple address transitions and verify proper decoder functionality across all 8 output lines with post-processing enabled for critical timing measurements.

instruction: I'm performing functional verification of a 768x256-bit SRAM macro operating at 3.3V supply voltage. The memory architecture employs a hierarchical organization with 12 banks of 64x64-bit sub-arrays, utilizing a 3-bit row address (ADD<2:0>) and 8-bit column selection. The testbench implements comprehensive write/read operations with precisely timed control signals: address setup at 50ns, clock rising edge at 25ns, write enable (WENB) activation at 100ns, and read output enable (RO) at 150ns. The simulation should execute transient analysis for 100ns to capture critical timing parameters including address-to-write setup (25ns), clock-to-output delay, and write pulse width (25ns). Please monitor all 64-bit data buses (WD<63:0> and RD<63:0>) while sweeping through multiple address combinations to verify proper cell access and data integrity across the entire memory array.

I'm characterizing a 128x256 SRAM array operating at 3.3V supply voltage for embedded memory applications. The memory architecture employs hierarchical organization with 64x64 sub-arrays using 6T bitcells and distributed I/O circuitry. Key timing parameters include: 50ns address setup time, 25ns clock rise time, 100ns write enable pulse width, and 150ns read output enable delay. The simulation should perform transient analysis of critical read/write operations with 1ns resolution over 100ns duration to verify access timing margins. Focus on measuring write margin by monitoring bitline development during write cycles to address 0x00 with alternating data patterns, and read stability by observing storage node disturbance during simultaneous read operations. Include worst-case process corner analysis using the BSIM3 nominal model library with proper convergence settings for the large-scale array simulation.

I'm characterizing a 512×256-bit SRAM macro operating at 3.3V supply voltage for embedded memory applications. The memory architecture employs hierarchical organization with 64×64-bit sub-arrays and features separate read/write data buses. Key timing parameters from the stimulus include: address setup time of 50ns with 100ps rise/fall times, clock pulse width of 25ns, write enable (WENB) activation at 100ns, and read output enable (RO) at 150ns. The address decoder uses a 3-bit input (ADD<2:0>) with periodic patterns (400ns, 800ns, 1600ns periods) to exercise different memory locations. I need to perform transient analysis to verify read/write functionality and timing margins. The simulation should run for 100ns with 1ns resolution, monitoring critical nodes including address inputs, control signals (CL, WENB, RO), and data buses (WD<63:0>, RD<63:0>). Please configure the analysis to capture setup/hold timing verification and signal integrity across the hierarchical memory structure.

I'm characterizing a 64x256-bit SRAM macro for embedded memory applications requiring high-density storage. The design employs a hierarchical architecture with four 64x64 RAM blocks organized in a 2D array, utilizing 6T SRAM cells with 0.4μm CMOS technology. Key specifications include: 3.3V supply voltage, 64-bit data bus width (WD<63:0>, RD<63:0>), 8-bit address input (AI<7:0>), and 64-bit data output (AO<63:0>). The timing parameters are critical: clock period of 25ns (40MHz), address enable (ADDENB) setup at 50ns, write enable (WENB) at 100ns, and read output (RO) at 150ns with 100ps rise/fall times.

I need to perform transient analysis to verify read/write functionality and timing margins. Configure the simulation for 100ns duration with 1ns resolution, monitoring all critical nodes including address decoding, bitline development, and sense amplifier operation. The analysis should validate write operations with data pattern generation (DGEN_256) and verify read access time from clock edge to valid data output. Include power supply monitoring and assess signal integrity across the hierarchical memory structure with proper convergence settings for accurate cell state transitions.

I'm characterizing an 8-line row decoder (Y-decoder) for a 3.3V SRAM memory array. The design goal is to validate the address decoding functionality and timing performance under realistic capacitive loading conditions. The topology implements a 3-to-8 decoder using complementary CMOS logic with three-stage architecture: input address buffers, NAND3 decoding gates, and dynamic latch-based output drivers. Key parameters include 3.3V supply voltage, 20pF output load capacitance per line representing bitline loading, and transistor geometries with 0.4μm channel length (PMOS W=20μ, NMOS W=10μ for NAND gates). The simulation requires transient analysis with 1ns resolution over 2μs duration to capture full address sequence timing. Input stimuli include three address bits (IN0, IN1, IN2) with 200ns, 400ns, and 800ns periods respectively, enable signal (ENB) with 200ns period, and clock (CL) with 25ns rise time. I need to verify proper one-hot output selection, measure address-to-output delay with 50ns setup time, and ensure no glitching during address transitions using BSIM3 models for accurate timing prediction.

I'm characterizing a 64×256-bit SRAM macro for embedded memory applications in a 3.3V CMOS process. The design employs a hierarchical architecture with four 64×64 RAM blocks organized in a 2D array, utilizing 8T SRAM cells with dedicated read/write ports. Key specifications include: 3.3V supply voltage, 64-bit data bus width (WD<63:0>, RD<63:0>), and 8-bit address input (AI<63:0>). The timing parameters are precisely defined with 25ns clock period (40MHz operation), 100ps rise/fall times for all control signals, and specific enable timing (ADDENB at 50ns, WENB at 100ns, RO at 150ns relative to clock edges).

I need to perform transient analysis to verify read/write functionality and access timing. The simulation should run for 100ns with 1ns resolution, monitoring all address, data, and control signals. Critical measurements include address-to-output delay (AI<63:0> to AO<63:0>), write enable to data valid timing (WENB to WD<63:0>), and read output stabilization (RO to RD<63:0>). The BSIM3 model library must be used with nominal process corners, and all convergence options should be set for robust memory simulation including proper initial conditions for storage nodes.

I'm characterizing a 64x64 SRAM macro for embedded memory applications requiring high-density on-chip storage. The design employs a hierarchical architecture with 3-bit address decoding, organized as eight 8x8 sub-arrays. Key specifications include: 3.3V supply voltage, 0.4μm NMOS/PMOS channel lengths with 4μm/3μm widths for the core 6T cells, and 20μm driver transistors for robust wordline driving. The memory features separate read (RO) and write (WENB) enable signals with 25ns clock period (40MHz operation).

Critical timing parameters from the stimulus include: 50ns address setup time, 0.1ns signal rise/fall times, and properly phased control signals (ADDENB, CL, RO, WENB) to ensure correct read/write sequencing. The simulation setup uses transient analysis with 1ns resolution over 100ns duration to capture multiple read/write cycles. I need to monitor all 64 data lines (RD, WD), address buses, and control signals to verify correct cell access, data retention, and timing margins. The analysis should include power consumption during active cycles and verify the hierarchical decoding logic functions correctly across all 4096 memory cells.

instruction: I am characterizing a complex 32-input NAND gate logic circuit for timing performance in a 5V CMOS digital system. The hierarchical design implements the 32-input function using a tree structure of basic NAND, NOR, and inverter cells, with each transistor having W=10μm and L=3μm dimensions. The circuit topology employs parallel PMOS pull-up networks and series NMOS pull-down networks in the NAND gates, with complementary arrangements in NOR gates. For timing analysis, I need to perform transient simulation with 0.01ns resolution over 4μs duration using Gear integration method. The simulation should measure propagation delays between input node V(11) and output nodes V(1) and V(7) for both rising and falling edges, using 2.5V (50% VDD) as the reference threshold. The testbench includes multiple stimulus patterns with pulse widths from 20ns to 140ns and rise/fall times of 10ns, with a 20fF load capacitance on critical nodes. Configure the simulation with post-processing enabled and activity threshold of 10mV for efficient analysis of the multi-stage logic path delays.

instruction: I'm characterizing the timing performance of a complex 32-input NAND gate logic circuit for high-speed digital applications. The design implements a multi-stage logic function using hierarchical subcircuits: basic 2-input NAND gates (10μm/3μm PMOS and NMOS), NOR gates, inverters, and an 8-input compound gate (INP8) that combines these elements. The main circuit topology employs four identical "head" blocks, each containing multiple INP8 subcircuits with NAND/NOR combinations driving a 20fF load capacitance. Key parameters include 5.0V supply voltage, 3μm channel length, and 10μm transistor widths across all devices. I need to perform transient analysis with 0.01ns resolution over 4μs duration to measure propagation delays through the critical paths. The simulation uses Gear integration method with specific FSS settings (10e-3 activity threshold, 10ps time unit) for numerical stability. Measurement statements will extract rise/fall delays between input V(11) and outputs V(1)/V(7) at the 2.5V threshold points for comprehensive timing characterization of this complex logic structure.

instruction: I am characterizing a differential amplifier circuit for high-speed analog applications requiring precise timing analysis. The topology consists of a differential pair with active current mirror load (X1, X2) and bias network (X3), operating from ±12V supplies. Key parameters include: 1kΩ collector resistors (RC1, RC2) with 0.003/°C temperature coefficient, 2kΩ bias resistor, 0.75pF load capacitance, and NPN transistors with β=80, RB=100Ω, CJC=0.2pF, CJE=0.3pF, and TF=0.03ns. The simulation performs three analyses: transient analysis with 5ns step to 80ns for propagation delay measurement using 0.25V input pulse, DC sweep from -0.25V to 0.25V for transfer characteristic verification against goal voltage VGOAL3, and AC analysis from 100kHz to 10GHz for frequency response. Critical measurements include propagation delay between input and output (DEL_V3_V1) with 2ns target, output voltage swing (MAX_TR_V3, MIN_TR_V3), and cross-point detection (CR_V3_V4_3). The optimization loop modifies bias resistance and load capacitance to achieve timing specifications while maintaining convergence with RELTOL=0.01 and 100 maximum iterations.
response:
DEMO CIRCUIT2. INPUT FILE
*
.SUBCKT  SUB1  1 2  3 
Q2  1 25 3  QNL
RS2  25 2  0.1K
.ENDS
.SUBCKT  SUB2  1 2 
Q3  1 2 VEE  QNL
Q4  2 2 VEE  QNL  1
.ENDS
.GLOBAL  VEE 
*......... PART I. COMPONENTS and CIRCUITS ........................
VIN  1 0  DC -0.25  PULSE( -0.25 0.25 1N 2N 2N 18N 40N )  AC 1
VEE  VEE 0  DC -12
VCC  8 0  DC 12
X1  3 1 6  SUB1
CLOAD  3 4  0.75PF
RC1  3 8  RMOD  1K
RBIAS  7 8  2K
X2  4 0 6  SUB1 
X3  6 7  SUB2 
RC2  4 8  RMOD  1K
VGOAL3  VGOAL3 0  PWLDC( -0.25V 12 -0.2V 11.97 -0.15V 11.9 -0.1V 11 
+ -0.05V 9.2 0V 5.6 0.05V 2.1 0.1V 0.8  0.15V 0.4 2V 0.31 2.5V 0.3)
RGOAL3  VGOAL3 0  -1
.MODEL QNL NPN(BF=80 RB=100 CCS=0.2PF TF=0.03NS TR=0.6NS
+              CJE=0.3PF CJC=0.2PF)
.MODEL RMOD R (TC1=0.003)
*........ PART II. ANALYSIS, OUTPUT and CONTROL CARDS .............
.TRAN  5NS 80NS 1NS 1.5NS  CALLV  SAVEV
.MEASURE  TRAN  MAX_TR_V3  MAX  V(3)
.MEASURE  TRAN  MIN_TR_V3  MIN  V(3)
.MEASURE  TRAN  FALL_1_TR_V3  WAVE  V(3)
+        FALL=1 VAL0=MIN_TR_V3 VAL1=MAX_TR_V3
.MEASURE TRAN  DEL_V3_V1  DELAY     V(1) RISE=1 VAL=0 
+        TARG=V(3) FALL=1 VAL0=MIN_TR_V3 VAL1=MAX_TR_V3
.MEASURE  TRAN  CR_V3_V4_3  CROSS  V(3) V(4) OCCUR=3
.DC  VIN  -0.25 0.25 0.05  CALLV 
.SNS  DC  V(3) V(X1.25) V(Q.X1.Q2#B) I(VIN) I(VCC) I(VEE) V(4)
+  TO
+ VIN(DC) RBIAS(RES) R.X1.RS2(RES)  QNL(RB)
+  TEMP GMIN  ARG=-0.25V 
.MEASURE  DC  ERR_V3_VGOAL3  ERR  V(VGOAL3) V(3)
.AC  DEC 10 100KHZ 10GHZ  CALLV  UIC
.MEASURE  AC  MAX_VM3  MAX  VM(3)
.MEASURE  AC  MIN_VM3  MIN  VM(3) TO=1MHZ
.MEASURE  AC  RISE_1_VM3  WAVE  VM(3)
+        COEF=0.01 RISE=1 VAL0=MIN_VM3 VAL1=MAX_VM3
.MODIF  RBIAS(RES)=2.5K  CLOAD(CAP)=0.75PF
+MODIF LOOP=5 STOP DEL_V3_V1 LE 2NS RBIAS(RES)*=0.9 CLOAD(CAP)*=0.6
.OPTIONS RELTOL=0.01 ABSTOL=1N VNTOL=50U ITL1=100 ITL2=50 ITL4=10 
+    ACCT NOMOD
.END

instruction: I am characterizing a two-bit BJT full adder circuit for digital computing applications. The design goal is to verify the functionality and timing performance of this bipolar integrated circuit implementing binary addition with carry propagation. The topology consists of two cascaded one-bit full adders built from nine NAND gates each, using a resistor-transistor logic (RTL) implementation with NPN transistors (BF=75, RB=100Ω, Cje=1pF, Cjc=3pF) and diode inputs. Key parameters include a 5V supply voltage, 4kΩ/1.6kΩ/1kΩ/130Ω resistor values in the NAND gates, and 1kΩ output loading. The simulation performs transient analysis over 400ns with 1ns resolution to capture the adder's response to input pulses (0-3V swing with 10ns rise/fall times and varying periods). I need to measure both static functionality verification and dynamic timing characteristics, specifically the propagation delays from input A1 to output BIT1 for both rising and falling edges, using 1.5V threshold crossings and 50% swing measurements. The simulation uses relaxed convergence settings (RELTOL=0.05) with accounting enabled to ensure robust operation while maintaining computational efficiency.
response:
EXAMPLE6: TWO-BIT BJT ADDER
*
.GLOBAL VCC
.SUBCKT NAND 1 2 3 
Q1  9 5 1  QNL
Q2  9 5 2  QNL
Q3  6 9 8  QNL
Q4  7 6 10 QNL
Q5  3 8 0  QNL
D1  0 1  DIOD
D2  0 2  DIOD
D3  10 3 DIOD
R1  VCC 5  4K
R2  VCC 6  1.6K
R3  8   0  1K
R4  VCC 7  130
.ENDS NAND
*************  INA INB CIN OUT COUT
.SUBCKT ONEBIT  1   2   3   4   5 
X1  1  2  7   NAND
X2  1  7  8   NAND
X3  2  7  9   NAND
X4  8  9  10  NAND
X5  3  10 11  NAND
X6  3  11 12  NAND
X7  10 11 13  NAND
X8  12 13 4   NAND
X9  11 7  5   NAND
.ENDS ONEBIT
.SUBCKT TWOBIT  INA1 INB1 INA2 INB2  BIT1 BIT2  CIN COUT 
X1  INA1  INB1  CIN  BIT1 10   ONEBIT
X2  INA2  INB2  10   BIT2 COUT ONEBIT
.ENDS TWOBIT
VINA1  1 0  PULSE( 0 3 0 10NS 10NS 10NS 50NS)
VINB1  2 0  PULSE( 0 3 0 10NS 10NS 20NS 100NS)
VINA2  3 0  PULSE( 0 3 0 10NS 10NS 40NS 200NS)
VINB2  4 0  PULSE( 0 3 0 10NS 10NS 80NS 400NS)
X1   1 2 3 4   BIT1 BIT2  0  COUT    TWOBIT
RB1  BIT1 0  1K
RB2  BIT2 0  1K
RCOUT   COUT 0  1K
VCC  VCC 0  DC 5
.MODEL QNL NPN(BF=75 RB=100 CJE=1PF CJC=3PF)
.MODEL DIOD D
.TRAN 1NS 400NS
.MEASURE TRAN MAX_BIT1 MAX  V(BIT1)
.MEASURE TRAN DEL_BIT1_INA1_RISE  DELAY V(1) RISE=4 VAL=1.5
+  TARG=V(BIT1) RISE=2 VAL0=0 VAL1=MAX_BIT1
.MEASURE TRAN DEL_BIT1_INA1_FALL  DELAY V(1) FALL=4 VAL=1.5
+  TARG=V(BIT1) FALL=2 VAL0=0 VAL1=MAX_BIT1
.OPTIONS  ACCT  RELTOL=0.05  NOMOD
.END

instruction: I'm designing a two-bit full adder circuit for high-speed digital applications using a 4.5V CMOS process. The topology implements a ripple-carry architecture with two cascaded one-bit full adders constructed from nine NAND gates each. The MOSFET parameters specify 1.3μm channel lengths with PMOS devices at 10μm width and NMOS devices at 5μm width, maintaining proper beta ratio. The technology uses 0.41nm gate oxide thickness with NMOS VTO=0.7V and PMOS VTO=-0.8V. Each NAND gate includes 55fF output capacitance for realistic loading. The simulation requires transient analysis over 60ns with 1ns resolution to characterize propagation delays and waveform integrity. Critical measurements include: carry propagation delay from CIN to BIT1 using 1.4V threshold, output pulse widths at internal carry nodes, and fall time analysis for both output bits between 0V and 4.5V thresholds. The input stimulus uses 2.8V to 0.4V pulses with 1ns rise/fall times and varying periods to exercise all adder combinations while monitoring timing performance.

C1  3  0  55FF
.ENDS NAND

X6  3  11 12  NAND

X9  11 7  5   NAND

.SUBCKT TWOBIT  INA1 INB1 INA2 INB2  BIT1 BIT2  CIN COUT  
X1  INA1  INB1  CIN  BIT1 10    ONEBIT
X2  INA2  INB2  10   BIT2 COUT  ONEBIT
.ENDS TWOBIT
VINA1  1 0  PULSE( 2.8 0.4 0 1NS 1NS 14NS 30NS)
VINB1  2 0  PULSE( 2.8 0.4 0 1NS 1NS 29NS 60NS)
VINA2  3 0  PULSE( 2.8 0.4 0 1NS 1NS 14NS 30NS)

VSS  VSS 0  DC 4.5
X1   1 2 3 4   BIT1 BIT2  CIN  COUT   TWOBIT 
.MODEL MOSP PMOS(LEVEL=3 VTO=-0.8  TOX=0.41E-7 UO=150    LD=0.14U 
+ KP=14U    ETA=0.014 THETA=0.042  VMAX=4.8E4  NFS=1E11  NSS=2E10
+ NSUB=2E16 JS=0.1M   GAMMA=0.68   KAPPA=0.24  XJ=0.45U  RSH=85 
+ PB=0.7    CJ=0.2M   CJSW=0.2N  )
.MODEL MOSN NMOS(LEVEL=3 VTO=0.7   TOX=0.41E-7 UO=500    LD=0.1U  
+ KP=28U    ETA=0.01  THETA=0.042  VMAX=1.9E5  NFS=1E11  NSS=2E10
+ NSUB=9E16 JS=0.1M   GAMMA=1.52   KAPPA=0.24  XJ=0.45U  RSH=85 
+ PB=0.7    CJ=0.2M   CJSW=0.2N  )

.MEASURE TRAN  MAX_COUT1  MAX  V(X1.10)
.MEASURE TRAN  DEL_BIT1_CIN  DELAY 
+       V(CIN)  FALL=1  VAL=1.4
+  TARG=V(BIT1) FALL=1  VAL0=0  VAL1=MAX_BIT1
.MEASURE TRAN  FALL_BIT2  WAVE
+  V(BIT2)  FROM=40NS FALL=1 VAL0=0 VAL1=4.5
.MEASURE TRAN  FALL_BIT1  WAVE
+  V(BIT1)  FROM=40NS FALL=1 VAL0=0 VAL1=4.5

+ TARG=V(X1.10) FALL=1 VAL0=0 VAL1=MAX_COUT1
.OPTIONS ACCT NOMOD
.END

This instruction characterizes a Wilson current mirror circuit for precision analog IC design, focusing on output impedance and sensitivity analysis. The three-transistor NMOS topology (M1-M3) provides high output impedance through cascode feedback. Key device parameters include: VTO=1.0V threshold voltage, KP=20μA/V² transconductance, LAMBDA=0.1V⁻¹ channel-length modulation, and TOX=0.1μm gate oxide thickness. The design operates with IIN=5μA reference current and VDS sweep from 0-2V in 20mV increments.

Execute DC analysis to characterize the output current versus drain voltage (VDS) while sweeping IIN from 0-10μA in 5μA steps. Perform sensitivity analysis using the SNS statement to quantify V(1) sensitivity to IIN(DC) and GMIN parameter variations with 10% perturbation (ARG=0.1). Extract the maximum node voltage MAX_V1 using measurement statements. Include model parameter modification (GMIN*=3) to assess process variation impact on circuit performance, with convergence settings (nomod) for robust simulation.

EXAMPLE3:  WILSON CURRENT MIRROR    
*
* THIS EXAMPLE SHOWS A HIGH SENSITIVITY OF THE WILSON CURRENT
* MIRROR WITH RESPECT TO THE INDEPENDENT CURRENT SOURCE IIN
* AND TO THE MOSFET MODEL PARAMETER GMIN.
*
VDS 3 0 DC 0
IIN 0 1 DC 5U  
M1  1 2 0 0  NE 
M2  2 2 0 0  NE  
M3  3 1 2 2  NE 
.MODEL  NE  NMOS  (VTO=1.0 LAMBDA=0.1 KP=20E-6 GAMMA=0.37
+    NSUB=5E14 TOX=0.1U LD=1.0U CJ=70U CJSW=220P CGSO=345P
+    CGDO =345P )
.DC  VDS  0. 2.0  0.02  IIN  0 10U 5U  CALLV SAVEV 
.SNS  DC  V(1)  TO  IIN(DC) GMIN  ARG=0.1
.MEASURE DC MAX_V1 MAX V(1)
.MODIF  MODIF  GMIN*=3
.options acct nomod
.END

instruction: I'm characterizing a three-stage CMOS inverter chain for low-noise digital applications requiring analysis of transient noise propagation. The topology consists of three identical cascaded inverter stages with parallel output transistors in the final stage to drive a 1pF capacitive load. The design uses asymmetric PMOS (W=5.6μm, L=1.3μm) and NMOS (W=4.0μm, L=0.8μm) transistors with body biasing at 4.7V for PMOS and 0.7V for NMOS to optimize threshold voltages. The simulation employs transient noise analysis with a 5V supply voltage and 50ns simulation time using 1ns resolution. The input stimulus is a 5V pulse with 1ns rise/fall times and 10ns pulse width at 45.5MHz frequency. Key measurements include maximum and minimum correlation coefficient k(out) to quantify noise correlation between input and output, with noise source defaults set to DEFNRD=1 and DEFNRS=1 for comprehensive device noise modeling. The analysis will determine how thermal and flicker noise propagates through the multi-stage digital buffer under realistic switching conditions.
response:
Example 2: Inverter Transient Noise Analysis 

.OPTIONS nomod DEFNRD=1 DEFNRS=1
.TRAN 1n 50n NOISE
.probe v(inp) v(out) k(out)

.PARAM w2p=5.6u w2n=4.0u bulkv=0.0
 
MP1 mid1  inp  vss pbulk    pmos w=5.6u  l=1.3u PS=33.45U AS=35.10P PD=33.45U AD=35.10P
MN1 mid1  inp  gnd nbulk    nmos w=4.0u  l=0.8u PS=19.50U AS=17.10P PD=19.50U AD=17.10P 

MP2 mid2  mid1 vss pbulk    pmos w='w2p' l=1.3u PS=33.45U AS=35.10P PD=33.45U AD=35.10P
MN2 mid2  mid1 gnd nbulk    nmos w='w2n' l=0.8u PS=19.50U AS=17.10P PD=19.50U AD=17.10P 

MP3  out  mid2 vss pbulk    pmos w=5.6u  l=1.3u PS=33.45U AS=35.10P PD=33.45U AD=35.10P  
MN3  out  mid2 0   nbulk    nmos w=4.0u  l=0.8u PS=19.50U AS=17.10P PD=19.50U AD=17.10P 

*     Parallel Transistors
MP33  out mid2 vss pbulk    pmos w=5.6u  l=1.3u PS=33.45U AS=35.10P PD=33.45U AD=35.10P  
MN33  out mid2 0   nbulk    nmos w=4.0u  l=0.8u PS=19.50U AS=17.10P PD=19.50U AD=17.10P 

Cout out 0 1pF

vs   vss 0   DC 5 
vin  inp 0  pulse(0 5 0 1n 1n 10n 22n) 

Vpbulk pbulk 0  DC 4.7  
Vnbulk nbulk 0  DC 0.7  

.MEASURE TRAN CorMAX MAX k(out)
.MEASURE TRAN CorMIN MIN k(out)
*================================================================================
 
.model nmos  nmos level=49
.model pmos  pmos level=49
.END

I'm designing a boost converter for power management applications requiring voltage step-up from a 10V DC input source. The topology employs a switched-inductor configuration with hysteretic current-mode control using a 254μH inductor and 516μF output capacitor. Key specifications include: 10V input voltage, 0.4V hysteretic control threshold, 20Ω load resistance, and 0.01Ω current sense resistor. The power stage uses a diode DNN with 0.1Ω series resistance and 1E-13A saturation current.

The simulation requires both transient and AC analysis to characterize converter performance. Transient analysis runs for 10ms with 10μs resolution to establish steady-state operation and measure the maximum output voltage at node 5. AC analysis sweeps from 1Hz to 10kHz with 10 points per decade to evaluate the control loop stability, specifically measuring the minimum phase margin at the output. The hysteretic controller implementation uses multiple nonlinear controlled sources with gain stages of 29 and 1000, along with current feedback through FB2 with -1 gain. Convergence is ensured through iterative parameter modification across three loops, adjusting control parameters including the hysteretic resistance from 0.4Ω to 0.5Ω and the reference voltage from 0.3V to 0.4V.

A7003 0 7003   v=v(7001)*v(7000)
.MODEL DNN D (IS=1.E-13 RS=.1 IBV=1.E-16)
.MODEL DIN D (IS=1.E-7 N=.85 RS=0.01 IBV=1.E-16)
*
.MODIF LOOP=3 VDON(DC)+=(0.3)0.1   GDON(TRCON)=1E-4
+      FB2(GAIN)=-1 HL(TRRES)=0.4 E4004(GAIN)=29  PRTBL
+MODIF LOOP=3 VDON(DC)+=(0.3)0.1  HL(TRRES)=0.5   PRTBL
*
.TRAN 10U 10M    TRANOP   SAVEV=10M    
.AC DEC 10 1 10K   CALLV   UIC 
.MEASURE TRAN maxV5 MAX V(5)
.MEASURE AC   min_PH_V5  MIN VP(5)
.MEASURE AC   expr_PH_V5 expr val="min_PH_V5*180/3.1416" 
.options acct nomod
.END

instruction: I'm designing a parallel RLC circuit for high-frequency filtering applications requiring precise resonance characterization. The topology consists of a 1kΩ resistor, 1μH inductor, and 1pF capacitor all connected in parallel between node 2 and ground. The design goal is to analyze the circuit's transient response and noise performance with an initial capacitor voltage condition of 5V. Key parameters are: R=1kΩ, L=1μH, C=1pF, yielding a theoretical resonant frequency of approximately 159MHz. The simulation employs transient analysis with a 0.0001ns initial time step over a 10ns duration, using initial conditions (UIC) and specialized noise analysis with zero initial noise conditions (NOISE_IC=ZERO). This setup will characterize the damped oscillatory behavior, quality factor, and noise propagation through the resonant tank circuit, providing critical validation of the filter's time-domain performance and noise characteristics for RF system integration.
response:
Example 3: Parallel RLC Circuit 
.option nomod

R1  2 0 1k
L1  2 0 1uH  
C1  2 0 1pF

.IC v(2)=5V
.tran 0.0001n 10n uic
+ NOISE NOISE_IC=ZERO 
.probe k(2) v(2)
.end

instruction:
I'm characterizing a standard cell inverter for a 65nm CMOS digital library. The goal is to perform a multi-variable corner analysis to extract critical timing, power, and process sensitivity metrics. The topology consists of a primary inverter driving a second, identically sized inverter with an explicit load capacitor of 1pF. The NMOS and PMOS devices have nominal channel lengths of 1.2μm and widths of 4μm and 10μm, respectively, operating from a 5V supply.

Key parameters for the corner analysis include supply voltage (vd=4.5V, 5V, 5.5V), input rise/fall times (1.5ns, 2ns, 2.5ns), and load capacitance (0.75pF, 1pF, 1.25pF). The process corners are defined by gate oxide thickness variation (tox=2.4nm ±0.2nm) and PMOS threshold voltage shift (vto0=-0.9V ±40mV).

The simulation employs both DC transfer characteristics and transient analysis. I need to measure the DC trip point of the first stage, propagation delays (rise and fall), their asymmetry, and average dynamic power consumption. The analysis must also extract the effective channel length and gate capacitance under these varying conditions to model process-voltage-temperature (PVT) effects accurately for library characterization.
response:
***  Cell Characterisation using .MODIF 
***   

************** Optional Parameters
.OPTIONS NOMOD FORMAT SAVEMEASURES
.OPTIONS SCALE=1u
.OPTIONS RELTOL=0.002

************** .MODIF statement
.MODIF LOOP=3 vd=    LIST(5   4.5   5.5 )
+             rise = LIST(2n  1.5n  2.5n )
+             fall = LIST(2n  1.5n  2.5n )
+             cap  = LIST(1pf 0.75p 1.25p)
+             PRTBL

************** Parameter Labels
.PARAM vd=5 rise=2n fall=2n 
.PARAM pw=10 nw=4  length=1.2 pl=1.2 cap= 1pf
.PARAM  tox = 2.400E-8  delta = 0.2e-8
.PARAM  vto0 = -0.9 deltavto=0.04 vtop='vto0+deltavto'
   
************** Global Net Declarations
.GLOBAL GND vdd

************** Circuit  Netlist
Vcc vdd GND  'vd'
Vin inp GND  DC 0 PULSE(0 vd 0ns rise fall 10ns 24ns ) 

Mn mid inp GND GND nmod W='nw' L='length'
Mp mid inp vdd vdd pmod W=pw L=length

X1  mid out  inv  nl=1.2 pl=1.4 vbb=0.0

************** Subcircuit  Definition
.SUBCKT inv  input output  nl=1.3  pl=1.3 vbb=-1
M1 output input GND vbias  nmod W=nw L=nl
M2 output input vdd vdd  pmod W=pw L=pl
Cload  output 0  'cap'
Vb  vbias  0 dc  'vbb'
.ENDS inv

************** Analysis Statements
.DC Vin 0 5v 0.025v 
.TRAN  0.1n 24n 
************** Output Statements
.SAVE i(c.X1.Cload) 
+     @m.X1.M1[L] 
+     @nmod[TOX]
.LET power='ABS(i(Vcc)*v(vdd))'
.LET Gcap = '@Mn[cgtot]'
************** Measurements
.MEASURE DC   max_c      MAX   'ABS(i(Vcc))'
.MEASURE DC   trip_p     CROSS v(mid) VAL= 'vd/2' 

.MEAS TRAN del_rise DELAY v(inp) VAL='vd/2' RISE=1
+                   TARG v(out)  VAL='vd/2' RISE=1
.MEAS TRAN del_fall TRIG v(inp) VAL='vd/2'  FALL=1
+                   TARG v(out)  VAL='vd/2' FALL=1
.MEAS TRAN  diff    EXPR  VAL='del_fall-del_rise'

.MEAS TRAN  avg_pow  AVG  power       
.MEAS TRAN  parL     MAX @m.X1.M1[L]   
*****************************************************************************
* Model Definitions
*
* Fast-Fast Transistor Model
*
.MODEL nmod     NMOS (                TOX= 'tox+delta'
+  BEX=-1.5                           LD=1.850E-7
+  WD=0.000E-7     NSUB=3.000E16      VTO=0.720
+  UO=630.00       DELTA=0.000        VMAX=1.950E5
+  XJ=3.0E-7       KAPPA=0.100        ETA=0.026
+  THETA=0.060     TPG=1              NFS=1.20E11
+  CJ=420E-6       CJSW=271E-12       PB=0.940
+  MJ=0.430        MJSW=0.160         CGDO=3.2E-10
+  CGSO=3.2E-10    CGBO=0
+  RSH=35.0        CAPMOD=2           LEVEL=3     )
*
.model pmod     PMOS (                TOX= 'tox+delta'
+  BEX=-1.5                           LD=2.70E-7
+  WD=-0.500E-7    NSUB=2.700E16      VTO= 'vtop'
+  UO=190.00       DELTA=0.000        VMAX=4.600E5
+  XJ=4.0E-7       KAPPA=0.100        ETA=0.042
+  THETA=0.100     TPG=1              NFS=0.50E11
+  CJ=392E-6       CJSW=373E-12       PB=0.880
+  MJ=0.460        MJSW=0.210         CGDO=3.2E-10
+  CGSO=3.2E-10    CGBO=0
+  RSH=60.0        LEVEL=3            )

.END

instruction: I need to perform comprehensive process corner characterization for a standard cell library inverter across multiple operating conditions. The design goal is to characterize propagation delay and power consumption for a 1.2μm CMOS technology inverter with fanout-of-one loading. The circuit topology consists of a two-stage inverter chain where the first stage drives an identical second stage with explicit load capacitance. Key parameters include: supply voltage variations (4.5V, 5V, 5.5V), input rise/fall times (1.5ns, 2ns, 2.5ns), and load capacitance (0.75pF, 1pF, 1.25pF). The NMOS device uses W=4μm/L=1.2μm while PMOS uses W=10μm/L=1.2μm. I require transient analysis with 0.1ns resolution over 24ns duration to measure both rise and fall propagation delays using 50% threshold crossing points. The simulation must sweep across Fast-Fast and Slow-Slow process corners with gate oxide thickness variations (2.4nm nominal ±0.2nm) and threshold voltage adjustments (PMOS Vt0=-0.9V ±40mV). Additionally, perform temperature sweeps at 27°C and 75°C using the .MODIF statement with loop=3 for comprehensive statistical coverage. Extract average dynamic power consumption and verify channel length matching through parametric measurements.
response:
* EXAMPLE 4 : Cell Characterisation using .MODIF and .ALTER 

* Characterisation of a cell using a combination of the 
* .MODIF and .ALTER statements.

************** Optional Parameters
.OPTIONS NOMOD FORMAT SAVEMEASURES
.OPTIONS SCALE=1u
.OPTIONS RELTOL=0.002 
.OPTIONS POST=2 

************** .MODIF Statement
.MODIF loop=3 vd=    LIST(5   4.5   5.5 )
+             rise = LIST(2n  1.5n  2.5n )
+             fall = LIST(2n  1.5n  2.5n )
+             cap  = LIST(1pf 0.75p 1.25p)
+             PRTBL 
+             PROFF

************** Parameter Labels
.PARAM vd=5 rise=2n fall=2n 
.PARAM pw=10 nw=4  length=1.2 pl=1.2 cap= 1pf
.PARAM  tox = 2.400E-8  delta = 0.2e-8
.PARAM  vto0 = -0.9 deltavto=0.04 vtop='vto0+deltavto'
   
************** Global Net Declarations
.GLOBAL GND vdd

************** Circuit  Netlist
Vcc vdd GND  'vd' 
Vin inp GND  DC 0 PULSE(0 vd 0ns rise fall 10ns 24ns ) 

Mn mid inp GND GND nmod W='nw' L='length'
Mp mid inp vdd vdd pmod W=pw L=length

X1  mid out  inv  nl=1.2 pl=1.4 vbb=0.0

************** Subcircuit  Definition
.SUBCKT inv  input output  nl=1.3  pl=1.3 vbb=-1
M1 output input GND vbias  nmod W=nw L=nl
M2 output input vdd vdd  pmod W=pw L=pl
Cload  output 0  'cap'
Vb  vbias  0 dc  'vbb'
.ENDS inv

************** Analysis Statement
.TRAN  0.1n 24n 

************** Output Statements
.SAVE i(c.X1.Cload) 
+     @m.X1.M1[L] 
+     @nmod[TOX]
.LET ThePower='ABS(i(Vcc)*v(vdd))'
.LET Gcap = '@Mn[cgtot]'

.MEAS TRAN del_rise DELAY v(inp) VAL='vd/2' RISE=1
+                   TARG v(out)  VAL='vd/2' RISE=1
.MEAS TRAN del_fall TRIG v(inp) VAL='vd/2'  FALL=1
+                   TARG v(out)  VAL='vd/2' FALL=1
.MEAS TRAN  diff    EXPR  VAL='del_fall-del_rise'

.MEAS TRAN  avg_pow  AVG  ThePower       
.MEAS TRAN  parL     MAX @m.X1.M1[L]  

*****************************************************************************
* Model Definitions
*
* Fast-Fast Transistor Model
*
.MODEL nmod     NMOS (                TOX= 'tox+delta'
+  BEX=-1.5                           LD=1.850E-7
+  WD=0.000E-7     NSUB=3.000E16      VTO=0.720
+  UO=630.00       DELTA=0.000        VMAX=1.950E5
+  XJ=3.0E-7       KAPPA=0.100        ETA=0.026
+  THETA=0.060     TPG=1              NFS=1.20E11
+  CJ=420E-6       CJSW=271E-12       PB=0.940
+  MJ=0.430        MJSW=0.160         CGDO=3.2E-10
+  CGSO=3.2E-10    CGBO=0
+  RSH=35.0        CAPMOD=2           LEVEL=3     )
*
.model pmod     PMOS (                TOX= 'tox+delta'
+  BEX=-1.5                           LD=2.70E-7
+  WD=-0.500E-7    NSUB=2.700E16      VTO= 'vtop'
+  UO=190.00       DELTA=0.000        VMAX=4.600E5
+  XJ=4.0E-7       KAPPA=0.100        ETA=0.042
+  THETA=0.100     TPG=1              NFS=0.50E11
+  CJ=392E-6       CJSW=373E-12       PB=0.880
+  MJ=0.460        MJSW=0.210         CGDO=3.2E-10
+  CGSO=3.2E-10    CGBO=0
+  RSH=60.0        LEVEL=3            )

************** .ALTER Statement

.ALTER
*****************************************************************************
* Model Definitions
*
* Slow-Slow Transistor Model
*
.MODEL nmod     NMOS (                TOX= 'tox+delta'
+  BEX=-1.5                           LD=1.850E-7
+  WD=0.000E-7     NSUB=3.000E16      VTO=0.720
+  UO=600.00       DELTA=0.000        VMAX=1.950E5
+  XJ=3.0E-7       KAPPA=0.100        ETA=0.026
+  THETA=0.060     TPG=1              NFS=1.20E11
+  CJ=520E-6       CJSW=300E-12       PB=0.940

instruction: I am characterizing the transient noise performance of a single NMOS transistor configured as a common-source amplifier for low-frequency analog applications. The design goal is to analyze how power supply voltage variation affects the integrated output noise voltage across the load capacitor. The circuit topology consists of an enhancement-mode NMOS device (L=0.28μm, W=2.6μm) with a 1pF capacitive load, biased by a pulsed input signal (0-5V with 200ns delay, 10ns rise/fall times) and drain supply voltages of 1V and 5V. Key parameters include drain/source areas of 1.274μm², perimeters of 6.18μm, and source/drain resistances of approximately 57.7Ω. The simulation employs transient noise analysis with accurate numerical settings, sweeping Vdrain from 1V to 5V while monitoring the noise integration factor k(vss). Critical measurements include maximum, minimum, and average noise correlation values between 800ns and 1200ns to capture steady-state noise behavior after circuit settling. The BSIM3v3.1 model (Level 49) at 27°C ensures accurate representation of modern sub-micron CMOS noise characteristics.
response:
Example 1: Transient Noise Analysis
.options nomod accurate

.param Vdrain = 1v
Vdd vdd 0 dc Vdrain
Vinput vin 0 PULSE(0 5 200n 10n 10n 1000n 1500n) 

.param nchwidth=2.6U
MU vdd vin vss 0 NENH L=.28U W=nchwidth
+ as='nchwidth*0.49u'   ad='nchwidth*0.49u' 
+ ps='nchwidth*2+0.98u' pd='nchwidth*2+0.98u'
+ nrd='0.15u/nchwidth'  nrs='0.15u/nchwidth'
Cload vss 0 C=1p 

.tran .1n 1500n NOISE SWEEP Vdrain LIST 2 1v 5v
.probe k(vss)

.MEASURE TRAN CORMAX MAX K(vss) FROM=800n TO=1200n
.MEASURE TRAN CORMIN MIN K(vss) FROM=800n TO=1200n
.MEASURE TRAN CORAVG AVG K(vss) FROM=800n TO=1200n

.model nenh NMOS
+ VERSION=3.1
+ Level = 49
+ Tnom = 27
.end

instruction:
I am characterizing a multi-stage CMOS inverter chain for high-speed digital applications, focusing on propagation delay matching and process variation sensitivity. The topology consists of a driver inverter (nmod/pmod) feeding a subcircuit inverter with configurable dimensions, creating a 2-stage buffer. Key design parameters include: 5V supply voltage, 1.2μm nominal channel length, 4μm NMOS width, 10μm PMOS width, and 1pF load capacitance. The analysis employs transient simulation with 0.1ns resolution over 24ns duration to capture switching behavior from a 2ns rise/fall time input pulse.

Critical measurements include rise/fall propagation delays (del_rise, del_fall) and their differential (diff) using precise 50% VDD crossing points. The simulation incorporates systematic process variation through conditional parameter sweeping: oxide thickness varies from 2.4nm to 2.6nm (±0.2nm), PMOS threshold voltage shifts from -0.9V to -0.86V (±0.04V), and load capacitance sweeps from 1pF to 1.2pF in 0.02pF increments. Convergence is ensured via RELTOL=0.002 and AUTOSTOP settings. This characterization will validate timing margins and identify sensitivity to manufacturing variations for robust digital circuit design.
response:
* Conditional Parameter Sweeping

************** Optional Parameters
.OPTIONS NOMOD FORMAT SAVEMEASURES
+ SCALE=1u
+ RELTOL=0.002
+ AUTOSTOP 
+ IPLOT_ONE 

************** .MODIF Statement
.MODIF loop=5  cap  *=(1pf)0.5 STOP del_rise LE 1ns PRTBL PROFF 
+MODIF loop=10 cap +=0.02pf    STOP 1ns LE del_rise PRTBL PROFF  
************** Parameter Labels
.PARAM vd=5 rise=2n fall=2n 
.PARAM pw=10 nw=4  length=1.2 pl=1.2 cap= 1pf
.PARAM  tox = 2.400E-8  delta = 0.2e-8
.PARAM  vto0 = -0.9 deltavto=0.04 vtop='vto0+deltavto'
   
************** Global Net Declarations
.GLOBAL GND vdd
.IPLOT v(out)

************** Circuit  Netlist
Vcc vdd GND  'vd' 
Vin inp GND  DC 0 PULSE(0 vd 0ns rise fall 10ns 24ns ) 

Mn mid inp GND GND nmod W='nw' L='length'
Mp mid inp vdd vdd pmod W=pw L=length

X1  mid out  inv  nl=1.2 pl=1.4 vbb=0.0

************** Subcircuit  Definition
.SUBCKT inv  input output  nl=1.3  pl=1.3 vbb=-1
M1 output input GND vbias  nmod W=nw L=nl
M2 output input vdd vdd  pmod W=pw L=pl
Cload  output 0  'cap'
Vb  vbias  0 dc  'vbb'
.ENDS inv

************** Analysis Statement
.TRAN  0.1n 24n  CALLV SAVEV 
************** Output Statements
************** Measurements

.MEAS TRAN del_rise DELAY v(inp) VAL='vd/2' RISE=1
+                   TARG v(out)  VAL='vd/2' RISE=1
.MEAS TRAN del_fall TRIG v(inp) VAL='vd/2'  FALL=1
+                   TARG v(out)  VAL='vd/2' FALL=1
.MEAS TRAN  diff    EXPR  VAL='del_fall-del_rise'

*****************************************************************************
* Model Definitions
*
* Fast-Fast Transistor Model
*
.MODEL nmod     NMOS (                TOX= 'tox+delta'
+  BEX=-1.5                           LD=1.850E-7
+  WD=0.000E-7     NSUB=3.000E16      VTO=0.720
+  UO=630.00       DELTA=0.000        VMAX=1.950E5
+  XJ=3.0E-7       KAPPA=0.100        ETA=0.026
+  THETA=0.060     TPG=1              NFS=1.20E11
+  CJ=420E-6       CJSW=271E-12       PB=0.940
+  MJ=0.430        MJSW=0.160         CGDO=3.2E-10
+  CGSO=3.2E-10    CGBO=0
+  RSH=35.0        CAPMOD=2           LEVEL=3     )
*
.model pmod     PMOS (                TOX= 'tox+delta'
+  BEX=-1.5                           LD=2.70E-7
+  WD=-0.500E-7    NSUB=2.700E16      VTO= 'vtop'
+  UO=190.00       DELTA=0.000        VMAX=4.600E5
+  XJ=4.0E-7       KAPPA=0.100        ETA=0.042
+  THETA=0.100     TPG=1              NFS=0.50E11
+  CJ=392E-6       CJSW=373E-12       PB=0.880
+  MJ=0.460        MJSW=0.210         CGDO=3.2E-10
+  CGSO=3.2E-10    CGBO=0
+  RSH=60.0        LEVEL=3            )

.END

instruction: I'm designing a wideband differential amplifier for instrumentation applications requiring high gain and low noise. The topology employs a fully differential input stage (Q1-Q2) with active loads, followed by a second gain stage (Q5-Q6) and buffered outputs (Q10-Q11). The circuit uses ±15V symmetric supplies and incorporates a current mirror bias network (Q7-Q9) with emitter degeneration for stability. Key parameters include: 4.8kΩ input stage load resistors, 1.32kΩ output stage resistors, and 5.25kΩ output loads. The NPN transistors are characterized by β=80, rb=100Ω, Cjc=2pF, Cje=3pF, and flicker noise KF=5.4e-16. I need comprehensive characterization including DC transfer analysis sweeping input from -0.25V to +0.25V in 5mV steps, AC analysis from 1Hz to 10GHz with 10 points per decade, and noise analysis from 20Hz to 1kHz with 20 points per decade. The simulation must compute output noise voltage at V(17) referenced to input source VIN, with detailed breakdown of individual device contributions including 1/f noise components. Set RELTOL=0.001 for convergence accuracy and enable accounting for simulation statistics.

instruction: I need to characterize the Meyer gate capacitance model for a 5μm/20μm NMOS transistor across various bias conditions to validate the capacitance-voltage relationships in our 0.5μm CMOS process design kit. The device under test has a gate oxide thickness of 97.7Å, threshold voltage of 1.0V, and uses LEVEL=3 model with CAPMOD=2 specifically for Meyer capacitance implementation. The simulation employs a transient analysis with a 5V pulse input (0-5V ramp over 5 seconds) to sweep the gate voltage linearly, where the measured currents through drain, source, and bulk terminals directly represent the gate capacitances cgd, cgs, and cgb respectively due to the extremely small KP=1e-19 and GMIN=1e-19 values that eliminate DC conduction. I require multiple simulation sweeps covering key operating regions: Vds=0V (linear), Vds=0.09V-0.11V (transition), Vds=0.8V (saturation), and Vbs=-0.5V (body effect), with additional analysis of substrate bias coefficient CF4 variation from 50 to 500. The transient settings use 0.05s time step with 0.025s maximum step for accurate capacitance extraction across the complete gate voltage sweep.
response:
MOSFET   M E Y E R    CAPACITANCES
*
*THIS FILE IS USED TO PLOT MEYER GATE CAPACITANCES
*CALCULATED DURING TRANSIENT ANALYSIS
*
V_G   G 0   PULSE( 0 5V  0 5S )
*  The derivative of the input signal V_G is equal to 1.0.
*  The parameters KP and GMIN of the MOSFET model are
*  very small(in order to remove DC currents). 
*  For this reason the currents i(V_D), i(V_B) and i(V_S)
*  represent Meyer capacitances cgd, cgb and cgs respectively.
V_D  D 0   DC 0 
V_B  B 0   DC 0 
V_S  S 0   DC 0
M1 D G S B   NM L=5e-6 W=20e-6
*
.MODEL  NM  NMOS( LEVEL=3  CAPMOD=2  
+               KP=1.0e-19
+               IS=0  VTO=1.0  TOX=9.77e-8  GAMMA=1.4 
+               NSUB=7.20e15  UO=817  PHI=0.6  VMAX=4.59e5
+               CJ=0 CJSW=0  JS=0) 
*
.TRAN  0.05  5S  0.01 0.025    
*
*  Using the .MODIF statement SmartSpice performs the
*  transient analysis four times for the following sets
*  of parameters:
*   1. V_D(DC) = 0     V_B(DC) =0     NM(CF4)=50
*   2. V_D(DC) = 0.11V V_B(DC) =0     NM(CF4)=50
*   3. V_D(DC) = 0.09V V_B(DC) =0     NM(CF4)=50
*   4. V_D(DC) = 0.8V  V_B(DC) =0     NM(CF4)=50
*   5. V_D(DC) = 0.8V  V_B(DC) =-0.5v NM(CF4)=50
*   6. V_D(DC) = 0.8V  V_B(DC) =-0.5v NM(CF4)=500
.MODIF   V_D(DC)=0
+MODIF   V_D(DC)=0.11V
+MODIF   V_D(DC)=0.09V
+MODIF   V_D(DC)=0.8V
+MODIF   V_B(DC)=-0.5V
+MODIF   NM(CF4)=500
*
.IPLOT i(V_D) i(V_S) i(V_B)
.OPTIONS  GMIN=1.0e-19   
.END

instruction:
I am characterizing a differential pair amplifier for low-frequency analog applications requiring high gain and linearity. The topology employs a bipolar junction transistor (BJT) long-tailed pair (Q1, Q2) with a 20kΩ current source bias resistor and an active current mirror load (Q3, Q4). The design targets a ±12V split supply (VEE=-12V, VCC=10V) with 10kΩ collector resistors (RC1, RC2) and a 5pF differential load capacitor. Key device parameters for the NPN transistors (model QNL) are a forward beta (BF) of 80, base resistance (RB) of 100Ω, forward transit time (TF) of 0.3ns, and Early voltage (VA) of 50V. Junction capacitances are specified as CJE=3pF and CJC=2pF.

The analysis suite includes a transient simulation to observe the large-signal time-domain response to a 100mV, 5MHz sinusoidal input, sweeping from 5ns to 500ns. A DC transfer characteristic analysis sweeps the input voltage VIN from -0.25V to +0.25V to determine the linear input range and gain. A small-signal AC analysis from 10kHz to 10GHz (10 points per decade) will extract the frequency response, voltage gain, and bandwidth. Furthermore, a statistical sweep of the forward beta (BF) from 80 to 100 in steps of 10 will be performed to evaluate performance sensitivity. Simulation accuracy is enforced with RELTOL=0.001.
response:
DEMO EXAMPLE 1: INPUT FILE
*
VIN  1 0  DC 0  SIN(0 0.1 5MEG)  AC 1
VCC  8 0  DC 10
VEE  9 0  DC -12
RS1  1 2  1K
RS2  5 0  1K
RC1  3 8  10K
RC2  4 8  10K
RBIAS  7 8  20K
CLOAD  3 4  5PF
Q1  3 2 6  QNL
Q2  4 5 6  QNL
Q3  6 7 9  QNL
Q4  7 7 9  QNL
.MODEL QNL NPN(BF=80 RB=100 CCS=2PF TF=0.3NS TR=6NS CJE=3PF CJC=2PF
+   VA=50)
.TRAN 5NS 500NS  
.DC VIN -0.25 0.25 0.025
.AC DEC 10 10KHZ 10GHZ 
.PRINT TRAN V(3) V(4)
.PRINT DC V(1) V(3) V(4) 
.PRINT AC VM(3) VP(3) 
.ST QNL(BF) 80 100 10
.OPTIONS ACCT RELTOL=0.001 NOMOD
.END

instruction: I am designing a fourth-order high-pass active-RC filter for anti-aliasing in a data acquisition system, targeting a Butterworth response for maximal flatness in the passband. The topology is a cascade of two Sallen-Key stages, with the first stage (R1=0.3827, C1=1, R3=0.3827, C2=1) and the second stage (R2=0.9239, C3=1, R4=0.9239, C4=1), both using ideal voltage-controlled voltage sources (E1, E2) with a gain of 1 as unity-gain buffers. The primary design goal is to perform a precise pole-zero (PZ) analysis to verify the filter's frequency response characteristics. The initial component values yield four real poles at -2.6130 and -1.0824. A subsequent modification (MODIF) adjusts resistors R3 to 2.61301 and R4 to 1.08237 to achieve the desired complex conjugate pole pairs for the Butterworth response: a pair at -0.9239 ± j0.38264 and another at -0.3827 ± j0.92387. The simulation is set to execute a pole-zero analysis (.PZ) from the input (node 10) to the output (node 6), printing all poles and zeros. This analysis is critical for confirming the filter's cutoff frequency and stability before proceeding with full AC and transient simulations.

This instruction describes a transient analysis of a two-input XOR gate for digital circuit characterization. The design goal is to verify the switching behavior and timing performance of a custom XOR cell implemented with a Verilog-A behavioral model. The circuit topology consists of two independent pulsed voltage sources driving the inputs of a single XOR gate instance with high-impedance output loading. Key parameters include: 5V input pulse amplitudes with 1ns rise/fall times, input pulse delays of 1μs (IN1) and 1.5μs (IN2) to create all four input combinations, and identical 2μs pulse widths with 4μs periods. The simulation employs transient analysis with 10ns resolution over a 7μs duration to capture the complete truth table sequence. The analysis will characterize propagation delays, output rise/fall times, and verify correct XOR functionality (0V output for matched inputs, 5V output for mismatched inputs) under the specified input stimulus conditions.
response:
* Two Input XOR Gate

.verilog "xor.va"

* Input Waveforms
vin1 in1 0 pulse(0 5 1u 1n 1n 2u 4u)
vin2 in2 0 pulse(0 5 1.5u 1n 1n 2u 4u)

* Instance Xor
YVLG_XOR in1 in2 out xorg

* Output Loading
RLoad out 0 1MEG

* Analysis
.tran 10n 7u

* Plot Waveforms
.print v(in1) v(in2) v(out)

.end

instruction: I'm designing a digital D-Flip Flop for high-speed sequential logic applications requiring precise timing characterization. The circuit topology implements a master-slave flip-flop using Verilog-A behavioral modeling with complementary outputs (q and qb). Key parameters include: 5V signal swing for both data and clock inputs, 1ns output loading capacitance on both outputs, and 4μs data pulse width with 8μs period. The clock signal operates at 250kHz (4μs period) with 50% duty cycle (2μs pulse width) and 1ns rise/fall times. I need to perform transient analysis to verify setup/hold timing requirements and propagation delays using 100ns sampling resolution over 20μs simulation duration. The simulation must capture the complete timing relationship between clock edges, data transitions, and output responses to validate proper flip-flop operation under the specified 5V CMOS logic levels.

* Clock
vclk clk 0 pulse (0 5 1u 1n 1n 2u 4u)

CLoadQB qb 0 1n

instruction: I am characterizing a 4-input XNOR logic gate for digital circuit verification in a 5V CMOS technology. Key parameters include: 5V signal swing with pulse rise/fall times of 1ns, input pulse widths of 2μs, and staggered input delays of 0μs, 0.3μs, 0.6μs, and 0.9μs to systematically exercise all 16 possible input combinations. The simulation employs transient analysis with a 100ns step size over a 7μs duration to capture multiple input transitions. The analysis will verify correct XNOR functionality (output high when even number of inputs high) and measure propagation delays and output transition times under various input pattern sequences.

instruction: I'm characterizing a master-slave JK flip-flop digital storage element for clock distribution networks in high-speed digital systems. The design goal is to verify correct sequential logic operation and timing performance under various input conditions. The circuit topology consists of a behavioral Verilog-A JK flip-flop model with active-high clock and asynchronous inputs. Key parameters include: 5V logic swing for all inputs, clock period of 6μs with 50% duty cycle (3μs high/3μs low), 5ns rise/fall times for all pulses, and 1MΩ output loading to minimize loading effects. The J input activates at 12μs with 16μs pulse width, K input activates at 8μs with 8μs pulse width, creating overlapping test conditions. I need to perform transient analysis from 0 to 100μs with 1μs resolution to capture all state transitions, including race conditions and setup/hold violations. The simulation should monitor all node voltages (clk, J, K, Q, Qbar) to verify truth table compliance and measure propagation delays through the flip-flop stages.
response:
* JK Flip Flop  

.verilog "jk_ff.va"

* * Input Waveforms
VCLOCK       clk            0      PULSE(0 5 4u   5n 5n 3u 6u)
VJ           j              0      PULSE(0 5 12u 5n 5n 16u 32u)
VK	     k              0      PULSE(0 5 8u  5n 5n 8u 16u)

* Instance JK Flip Flop
YVLG_JK_FF    j k clk      q qbar  V_jk_ff

* Output Loading

RLOAD_QBAR     qbar    0       1MEG

.tran 1u 100u

.print v(clk) v(j) v(k) v(q) v(qbar) 
*.iplot v(clk) v(j) v(k) v(q) v(qbar) @YVLG_JK_FF[V(q)]

.end

instruction: I am characterizing a reset-set (RS) flip-flop digital memory cell for validation in a mixed-signal IC. The outputs are loaded with 1pF capacitors to model realistic interconnect and fanout loading. I need to perform a transient analysis from 0 to 30μs with 1μs resolution to capture the complete state transition sequence, including the forbidden state when both set and reset are simultaneously active. instruction: I'm characterizing a Verilog-A BJT model for circuit design applications, specifically analyzing its DC operating characteristics and output behavior. The testbench implements a common-emitter configuration with the collector connected through a 10mΩ resistor to a 2.0V supply (V3) and the base driven through a 1.0Ω resistor from a variable DC source (V1). The emitter is directly grounded through terminal 4. The design goal is to extract the complete DC transfer characteristics including collector current, base current, and output voltage swing. Key parameters include: base resistance (rb=1Ω), collector resistance (rc=1Ω), emitter resistance (re=1Ω), collector supply sweep from 0.0V to 2.0V in 10mV steps, and base voltage sweep from 0.5V to 0.6V in 25mV increments. The simulation uses DC analysis with convergence acceleration disabled (conv=0) to ensure numerical stability while measuring voltages at nodes 1 and 3, along with currents through all voltage sources to characterize the complete I-V relationship and Early effect.
response:
* bjt veriloga

.verilog "bjt.va"

.option conv=0 nomod brief

v1 11 0 dc 0.5
v3 33 0 dc 2.0
v4 4  0 dc 0.0

r1 11 1 1.0
r3 3 33 0.01

YVLGbip 3 1 0 4 NBJT

.dc v3 0.0 2.0 0.01 v1 0.5 0.6 0.025

.print v(3) v(1) i(v1) i(v3) i(v4)

.model NBJT VLG module=bjt
+ rb=1
+ rc=1
+ re=1

.end

instruction: I'm designing a mixed-signal phase-locked loop for clock generation in a 3.3V CMOS system. The PLL architecture consists of a Verilog-A phase detector, SPICE charge pump with current matching, second-order passive loop filter, Verilog-A voltage-controlled oscillator, and programmable frequency divider. Key specifications include: 3.3V supply voltage, 100MHz reference clock with 50% duty cycle (10ns period, 4.9ns pulse width), and initial VCO control voltage of 1.1V for fast locking. The loop filter uses RC components with 100Ω series resistance and 1pF load capacitance. I need to perform transient analysis to characterize locking behavior and stability over 2μs simulation time with 0.1ns resolution. The simulation must monitor critical nodes including reference/feedback phases, charge pump outputs (up/down signals), filter voltage, and divided clock to verify proper phase acquisition and steady-state operation with accurate convergence settings.
response:
* PLL (Phase-Locked Loop) 
* SPICE/Verilog-AMS Mixed Simulation
 
 * Verilog-A module files 
.verilog "pll_pd.va"
.verilog "pll_vco.va"
.verilog "divider.va"

* Libary
.lib  'bsim3_example.lib'  typical

* Parameters
.global  vdd

* Options
.options  acct nomod accurate

* SPICE Subcircuit files

.include "pll_cp.net"                       ; Charge Pump 
.include "pll_lpf.net"                      ; Loop Filter 

* PLL Main Circuit
YVLG_PD   ref     fb    up   down  pll_pd   ; Phase Detector  - Verilog-A module
Xcp      up      down  lpf        pll_cp    ; Charge Pump     - SPICE subcircuit
Xlpf     lpf                      pll_lpf   ; Low-pass filter - SPICE subcircuit
YVLG_VCO lpf     ckout1           pll_vco   ; Voltage Controlled Oscillator - Verilog-A module
YVLG_DIV ckout   fb               divider   ; Devider - Verilog-A module
r1       ckout1  ckout   100
c1       ckout   0       1p

* Input Waveforms
vref ref 0 pulse(0 3.3 22.4n 0.1n 0.1n 4.9n 10n) 
vvdd vdd 0 3.3 

* Initial conditions
.ic   v(xlpf.cap)=1.1  v(up)=0.0  v(down)=0.0

* Analysis 
.tran 0.1n 2u

* Save Waveforms
.save v(ref) v(fb) v(up) v(down) v(lpf) v(ckout) 

.end
